        <h4 class="cat-section-title-1"><a href="/topic/broad-topics/health-technology" class="cat-link-primary">See all</a><span>Most Recent in Health Technology</span></h4>




        
        <div class="most-recent-in-topic"><ul><li><div class="issue-item clearfix issue-item_lg-img"><div class="issue-item_top"><a href="/topic/catalyst-article-type/article" title="Article">Article</a><span class="issue-item_date"></span></div><div class="issue-item_cont clearfix"><div class="issue-item_left"><h6 class="issue-item_title"><a href="/doi/full/10.1056/CAT.20.0100" title="">Rapid System Transformation to More Than 75% Primary Care Video Visits within Three Weeks at Stanford: Response to Public Safety Crisis during a Pandemic</a></h6><div class="issue-item_authors">By <ul><li>Maja Artandi, </li><li>Samuel Thomas, </li><li>Nirav R. Shah</li><li> & Malathi Srinivasan</li></ul></div><div class="issue-item_text"><p><p>Stanford Primary Care scaled a nascent video visit program in two Express Care urgent care centers to cover more than 80% of clinic visits within 2 weeks.</p></p></div></div></div></div></li><li><div class="issue-item clearfix issue-item_lg-img"><div class="issue-item_top"><a href="/topic/catalyst-article-type/article" title="Article">Article</a><span class="issue-item_vol"><a href="/toc/catalyst/1/3">VOL. 1 No. 3</a></span><span class="issue-item_date"></span></div><div class="issue-item_cont clearfix"><div class="issue-item_left"><h6 class="issue-item_title"><a href="/doi/full/10.1056/CAT.20.0132" title="">The Agenda for the Next Generation of Health Care Information Technology</a></h6><div class="issue-item_authors">By <ul><li>Thomas W. Feeley, </li><li>Zachary Landman</li><li> & Michael E. Porter</li></ul></div><div class="issue-item_text"><p><p>To make the transition to value-based health care, health care information technology systems must be transformed to enable data collection, data sharing, and usability by patients and providers.</p></p></div></div></div></div></li><li><div class="issue-item clearfix issue-item_lg-img"><div class="issue-item_top"><a href="/topic/catalyst-article-type/article" title="Article">Article</a><span class="issue-item_date"></span></div><div class="issue-item_cont clearfix"><div class="issue-item_left"><h6 class="issue-item_title"><a href="/doi/full/10.1056/CAT.20.0093" title="">The Transition from Reimagining to Recreating Health Care Is Now</a></h6><div class="issue-item_authors">By <ul><li>Judd E. Hollander</li><li> & Frank D. Sites</li></ul></div><div class="issue-item_text"><p><p>The Covid-19 outbreak has created some quick, short-term opportunities for providers and patients to embrace telemedicine. And while the coronavirus-related exposure to and experience with this health care tool may help accelerate acceptance, clinicians must adopt a long-term, post-pandemic approach to ensure success.</p></p></div></div></div></div></li></ul></div>
</div>

